Fundamentals of Visual Design
Theory Assignments
1. Study on Design Principles: Explain principles like contrast, balance, and hierarchy with examples.
•	Contrast: The distinct visual variance between two adjacent interface layout elements. Example: Placing bright yellow primary interactive action buttons directly on top of dark charcoal background themes.
•	Balance: The specific distribution weight assigned across structural elements throughout layout systems. This can be organized symmetrically or asymmetrical. Example: Placing text details evenly opposite a prominent image layout component on desktop views.
•	Hierarchy: The practice of organizing layout pieces to control the exact sequence users view them. Example: Rendering a dominant bold heading title at 36px, sub-headings at 20px, and standard body text blocks at 16px.
2. Color Theory: Write a report on color psychology and its impact on design. Colors create direct emotional responses and establish critical product context:
•	Blue: Conveys security, structure, and professional validation (e.g., PayPal, LinkedIn, major banking platforms).
•	Red: Signals urgency, error responses, or high energy (e.g., Netflix, dynamic clearance notification markers).
•	Green: Reflects organic growth, health tracking, or successful confirmation events.
Practical Assignments (Implementation Blueprints)
•	Mood Board Creation: Consolidate clean visual references across layout palettes, graphic themes, and structural designs to lock down concrete brand guidelines before writing code.
•	Typography Task: Pick standard pairings based on product style goals. Example: Clean sans-serif pairings (Inter / Roboto) for high-tech applications.
•	Layout Design: Implement consistent layout grids (like standard 12-column frameworks) to manage alignment and structural spacing uniformly.
