Wireframing and Prototyping
Theory Assignments
1. Wireframing Basics: Explain the importance of wireframes in the design process and differences between low- and high-fidelity wireframes. Wireframes serve as structural blueprints, mapping layout placement configurations without visual details like branding elements or final imagery.
Metric	Low-Fidelity Wireframe	High-Fidelity Wireframe
Visual Detail	Monochrome boxes, placeholder text lines.	Production typography, exact padding, colors.
Speed	Built in minutes via sketch blocks or fast digital layouts.	Takes hours, requires precise design system structures.
Focus	Ideation, functional flow, layout logic.	Micro-interactions, visual design validation.
2. Prototype Fundamentals: Write about the stages of prototyping and its benefits in product development.
•	Development Stages:
1.	Paper Sketches: Fast physical exploration of layout concepts.
2.	Clickable Low-Fi Layouts: Structural page flows connected via interactive hotspots.
3.	Hi-Fi Prototypes: Detailed interactive assets using precise variable states and complex transition behaviors.
•	Core Benefits: Identifies navigation issues before writing frontend code, aligns technical engineering teams with product goals, and reduces costly re-coding requests during active development cycles.
Practical Assignments (Implementation Blueprints)
•	Low-Fidelity Wireframe: Sketch a standard e-commerce page block outline focusing on navigation headers, main hero images, functional grid selectors, and footer targets.
•	Prototype Creation: Wire hot-link connections between primary app elements within Figma to build basic user flows.
•	Feedback Loop: Run short usability validation passes with users to locate navigation issues, then implement structural adjustments based on those observations.
