Interaction Design and Micro Interaction
Theory Assignments
1. Introduction to Interaction Design: Describe interaction design principles with examples of good and bad interactions.
•	Core Principles:
o	Visibility: Interactive components should explicitly look like they can be clicked or tapped.
o	Feedback: The interface must respond clearly to every user input action.
•	Good Interaction: A button that changes state upon hover and turns into a loading spinner once clicked, providing immediate status updates.
•	Bad Interaction: An un-styled textual link element that gives zero visual confirmation upon submission, forcing users to repeatedly click the button.
2. Microinteractions: Write about the importance of microinteractions and how they enhance user experience. Microinteractions are subtle, isolated single-task interaction moments built into an app. They handle small tasks like toggling system dark-mode switches, pulling to refresh page feeds, or displaying confirmation checkmarks.
•	UX Value: They make interfaces feel responsive and organic, provide clear status confirmation, and guide user navigation paths effortlessly.
Practical Assignments (Implementation Blueprints)
•	Button Animation: Define smooth state styles via CSS selectors (:hover, :active) paired with clean layout transitions (transition: all 0.2s ease).
•	Feedback Interaction: Build animated checkmarks using custom keyframe styles (@keyframes) that scale up smoothly upon successful form inputs.
•	Tooltips and Notifications: Position automated absolute tooltip text containers that display contextual info when users hover over interface help elements.
