Advanced Prototyping and Usability Testing
Theory Assignments
1. Usability Testing: Write a guide on planning and conducting usability testing sessions.
•	Step 1: Define Goals: Isolate exactly what flows require evaluation (e.g., assessing checkout drop-off rates).
•	Step 2: Recruit Testers: Select 5–8 targeted users who match defined core user personas.
•	Step 3: Build Action Scenarios: Write clear tasks (e.g., “Find a blue jacket under $50 and purchase it”) rather than telling them how to use the UI.
•	Step 4: Moderate Sessions: Instruct participants to speak out loud as they navigate the interface, and record layout points where they encounter confusion.
•	Step 5: Synthesize: Group observed interface issues by severity, then prioritize structural modifications.
2. Usability Metrics: Explain key metrics used to evaluate usability (e.g., task success rate, error rate).
•	Task Success Rate (TSR): The absolute percentage of users who complete a core system flow without assistance.
•	Error Rate: The average total number of incorrect formatting submissions or wrong clicks recorded per user profile during a task.
•	Time on Task: The specific time measurement a user takes to successfully complete an assignment flow.
•	System Usability Scale (SUS): A post-test survey metric calculated to score overall subjective satisfaction out of 100.
Practical Assignments (Implementation Blueprints)
•	High-Fidelity Prototype: Link complex screen transitions together inside your design application using realistic data inputs and modal view changes.
•	Conduct a Usability Test: Run tests using your high-fidelity flows with target users, noting exactly where they experience input confusion.
•	Refinement: Update layout structures by removing confusing input elements or adding clearer form guidelines.
