Accessibility and Inclusive Design
Theory Assignments
1. Accessibility Basics: Discuss WCAG guidelines and their importance in inclusive design. The Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) build digital standards around four fundamental criteria (POUR):
•	Perceivable: Information and user interface components must be presentable to users in ways they can perceive (e.g., adding text alternatives for non-text content).
•	Operable: Interface components and navigation must be operable (e.g., allowing full keyboard-only navigation access).
•	Understandable: Information and the operation of user interface must be understandable (e.g., input forms must provide clear, explicit error instructions).
•	Robust: Content must be robust enough that it can be interpreted reliably by a wide variety of user agents, including screen readers.
2. Inclusive Design: Write about how accessibility impacts user experience and the benefits of inclusive design. Inclusive design builds flexible product pathways useful for users across all cognitive or physical capability levels.
•	Impact & Benefits: Implementing accessibility features benefits all users—high-contrast text ensures view readability outside in bright sunlight, while clear closed captions allow content access in loud public environments. It also expands overall market reach and prevents legal non-compliance issues.
Practical Assignments (Implementation Blueprints)
•	Accessibility Audit: Evaluate pages using testing tools to locate visual color issues or missing image label elements.
•	Accessible Redesign: Update styling structures to hit at least 4.5:1 color contrast ratios, add explicit labels to input elements, and ensure focus visible states display clearly.
•	Simulated Experience: Test navigating your pages using native desktop screen readers with the display turned off to check if structural tag orders read logically.
