Mobile and Responsive Design
Theory Assignments
1. Responsive vs. Adaptive: Write a report on the differences between responsive and adaptive design with examples.
•	Responsive Design: Uses fluid layout frameworks that dynamically resize to fill any available screen real estate. Example: A website built with percentage-based grid parameters that stretches smoothly from small smartphone screens up to wide computer monitors.
•	Adaptive Design: Targets specific device viewport sizes using distinct layout configurations optimized for fixed device targets. Example: A server that detects a smartphone user agent and serves up a distinctly custom mobile layout structure.
2. Mobile-First Design: Explain why mobile-first design is critical in modern UX. Mobile-first design structures the product experience for restricted mobile screen viewports first, then scales up features for large desktop screens later.
•	Critical Value: It forces design teams to strip out secondary feature fluff and prioritize core content. Technically, it ensures fast loading speeds over mobile data connections and guarantees compatibility with mainstream touch-based browsing usage.
Practical Assignments (Implementation Blueprints)
•	Responsive Layout: Build out layouts that stack multi-column elements into clean single-column presentation rows on smaller screens.
•	Mobile App Layout: Structure navigation systems around bottom bar patterns for easy thumb reach, avoiding tiny desktop hover menus.
•	Breakpoints Implementation: Add clean media queries to transform layout structures across tablet and mobile targets.
