Design Handoff and Collaboration
Theory Assignments
1. Design Handoff Process: Explain the handoff process and best practices for working with developers. The handoff process translates final visual design mockups into engineering packages for developer implementation.
•	Best Practices: Involve engineering teams early during layout ideation to verify code feasibility. Organize clean component state variations (Default, Hover, Active, Disabled), use strict layout token naming rules for padding and colors, and supply optimized SVG icon assets alongside layouts.
2. Collaboration Tools: Write about tools (e.g., Zeplin, Figma Inspect) that facilitate collaboration and handoff. Platforms like Figma Inspect or Zeplin serve as centralized collaboration bridges. They allow engineering teams to click structural mockups to inspect exact spacing specs, download optimized graphic assets directly, and read layout styling information (CSS properties, font sizing configurations, color tokens) without messing up the primary source layout design files.
Practical Assignments (Implementation Blueprints)
•	Prepare Design Specs: Document precise layout sizing variables, explicit typeface scales, and color hex maps for cross-team use.
•	Component Documentation: Build complete documentation outlining design components, variant parameters, and usage rules.
•	Collaborative Project: Walk through a mockup package with developer teammates, using layout inspection modes to verify implementation requirements.
