Introduction to Website Design and HTML Basics
Theory Assignments
1. Explain the structure of an HTML document and the purpose of DOCTYPE.
•	<!DOCTYPE html>: Declares the document type and ensures the browser renders the page using the modern HTML5 standard standard compliance mode.
•	<html>: The structural root element enclosing all page content.
•	<head>: Contains essential page metadata, charset specifications, viewport definitions, and external style sheets.
•	<body>: Contains the visible structural content of the webpage rendered to users.
2. List and explain at least five common HTML tags used in website design.
•	<h1> to <h6>: Structural header elements indicating typographic hierarchy levels.
•	<p>: Wraps blocks of standard paragraph text.
•	<a>: Creates hyperlinks using the href attribute to link external pages or internal sections.
•	<img>: Embeds image media assets into pages using source (src) and descriptive alternative text (alt) attributes.
•	<div>: A generic block-level container element used to group structural components for layout styling purposes.
3. Describe the difference between block-level and inline elements in HTML.
•	Block-Level Elements: Start on a fresh line, stretch horizontally to fill the full available width of their parent container, and can have custom top/bottom padding and margin values set (e.g., <div>, <h1>, <p>, <video>).
•	Inline Elements: Do not start on a fresh line, only take up as much horizontal width as their internal content requires, and wrap alongside adjacent content without breaking layout flow (e.g., <a>, <span>, <strong>, <img>).

Theory Assignments
1. Explain the difference between inline, internal, and external CSS.
•	Inline CSS: Style properties applied directly onto HTML markup components via the local style attribute. High maintenance, lacks structural modularity.
•	Internal CSS: Rules written directly within <style> tag elements located inside the document <head> structural wrapper. Affects only that single specific page.
•	External CSS: Clean rules declared inside standalone .css assets linked to HTML documents via <link> tags. This approach allows global style updates and helps pages load faster through browser caching.
2. Describe CSS selectors and list the types of selectors (e.g., element, class, id). Selectors pinpoint exactly which HTML tags receive specific CSS visual configurations.
•	Element Selector: Selects all targets sharing that tag identity (e.g., p { color: blue; }).
•	Class Selector: Selects elements matching defined class attributes. Indicated via dots (e.g., .card-layout { padding: 20px; }).
•	ID Selector: Targets a unique element id value. Indicated via hash symbols (e.g., #main-header { width: 100%; }).
3. Discuss the CSS box model and its components. Every structural object rendered on a web page is treated as a rectangular box layout. The components are structured outward as follows:
+-----------------------------------------------------+
| MARGIN |
| Clears an area outside the structural border line. |
| +-------------------------------------------------+ |
| | BORDER | |
| | Wraps tightly around padding and main content. | |
| | +---------------------------------------------+ | |
| | | PADDING | | |
| | | Clears structural space around content box. | | |
| | | +-----------------------------------------+ | | |
| | | | CONTENT | | | |
| | | | The raw text or graphic asset space. | | | |
| | | +-----------------------------------------+ | | |
| | +---------------------------------------------+ | |
| +-------------------------------------------------+ |
+-----------------------------------------------------+
